@jch that might be _similar_ to how we're testing `Net::LDAP::Connection` socket events:
https://github.com/ruby-ldap/ruby-net-ldap/blob/0aeceaffd4ad75e03049e30cbf935cd77da3d8e9/test/test_ldap_connection.rb#L187-L204

The problem here is that what we want to test is that this works as we expect, that we've crafted the correct query to trigger the proper behavior. I can independently verify that the query is valid and works as expected, and once that's done we can create a test case to verify that the query the validator uses matches the verified query. Sound sane?

review_comments.body:
Why not default `:detect` in the method parameter?

``` ruby
def configure_membership_validation_strategy(strategy = :detect)
  @membership_validator ||= strategy.to_sym
end
```

@jch agree in some senses, but there are two separate classes that depend on the same behavior that didn't feel right duplicating in (the ActiveDirectory MemberSearch and MembershipValidation strategies). It's a mix of AD-specific feature detection with general capability exposure.

I'm not crazy about it, but it unblocks this PR and can be easily changed in the future when a better approach can be considered, particularly because it's internal only. I think this need will diminish with the changes you outline in https://github.com/github/github-ldap/pull/69#discussion_r21327407, so it is likely temporary.

Thoughts?

Can we restructure this into:

``` ruby
@options = {
  :attributes => [],
  :paged_searches_supported => true,
  :size => 1
}
```

